  "updated_summary": "Jan VandeBurie explained that nobility viewed the Crusade as a means to carve out kingdoms or find glory, as an animated map showed Crusader routes towards Constantinople and the Holy Land, accompanied by epic orchestral music and sounds of horses and clashing swords. Qassem Abdu Qassem reiterated that armies departed from Western Europe for the Holy Land, with some seeking to defend their reputation and others aiming to acquire new land, as a cinematic battle scene unfolded with Crusader Knights and Arab Warriors clashing fiercely. The animated map zoomed in on Constantinople, before cutting to a regal figure, identified as the Byzantine Emperor Alexius, seated on a golden throne in an ornate interior, flanked by attendants and guards. The Emperor, historically identified as Komnenos, contemplated a scroll in a dimly lit, ornate chamber, as Crusader envoys in medieval European attire stood before him, flanked by Byzantine guards. The Emperor demanded their allegiance and the return of reconquered lands. Said Al-Bishawy explained that the Crusaders needed Byzantium's help for provisions and guidance, detailing the Emperor's conditions: an oath of loyalty and obedience, and the return of all conquered lands, ensuring Byzantine territories would return to Byzantium. The envoys raised their hands in pledge, agreeing to the terms, after which Al-Bishawy stated the Emperor granted them passage into Asia Minor. An ominous musical score began as the regal figure, adorned in richly embroidered robes and a golden crown, sat on an ornate throne. A narrator explained that after crossing the Bosphorus, the Crusaders marched towards the Seljuk's capital, Nicaea. Mahmoud Imran explained how Christian soldiers disguised themselves in Seljuk uniforms and approached Nicaea from behind via a lake, riding boats to cross undetected, as a nighttime reenactment showed Crusaders in boats navigating under a stone archway. Imran continued that the Seljuk Sultan was absent, and their leadership was caught by military shock, allowing the Crusaders to succeed in controlling the capital, marking 'the first step.' Dramatic orchestral music accompanied a historical painting of a massive medieval battle, followed by a reenactment of Crusader Knights riding through a barren landscape. The narrator stated that Nicaea was returned to the Byzantines, and as the Crusaders continued their march in Asia Minor, their task of taking Jerusalem was set aside. Baldwin of Boulogne decided to abandon the armies heading southwards and, at the invitation of its Armenian Christian ruler, marched east to Edessa. An animated map traced the Crusaders’ route from Constantinople through Nicaea, Caesarea, and toward Edessa. Jonathan Phillips explained that Baldwin I moved towards Edessa, a strategically important place. A silhouette of a Crusader raising a flag atop a fortress symbolized victory, as triumphant music swelled and sounds of cheering emerged."
